{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609046"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:40:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:40:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16071"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16071"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8762"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110235"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8762"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92506"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7615"},{"type":"tags","id":"7620"},{"type":"tags","id":"10745"},{"type":"tags","id":"10748"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20942"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21619"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110235"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIn female mammals, one X chromosome must be inactivated in each cell to prevent overexpression of X-linked genes compared to males. This process occurs during early embryonic development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of X chromosome inactivation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alternating expression between maternal and paternal X chromosomes","Physical degradation of one X chromosome","Random silencing of one X chromosome by XIST RNA","Reduced expression from both X chromosomes","Permanent deletion of X chromosome genes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct mechanism involves \u003Cstrong\u003Erandom silencing of one X chromosome by XIST RNA\u003C/strong\u003E. During early embryonic development, the X inactivation centre produces XIST (X-inactive specific transcript) RNA, which coats and inactivates one randomly chosen X chromosome. The inactive state is then maintained through DNA methylation and histone modifications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlternating expression between maternal and paternal X chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E - Once established in a cell, the same X chromosome remains inactive through all subsequent divisions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhysical degradation of one X chromosome\u003C/strong\u003E - The X chromosome remains physically present but is transcriptionally silenced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced expression from both X chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E - One X chromosome is completely inactivated rather than both being partially expressed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPermanent deletion of X chromosome genes\u003C/strong\u003E - Genes are silenced through epigenetic mechanisms, not deleted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis process ensures that females do not have double the expression of X-linked genes compared to males, maintaining appropriate gene dosage between the sexes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["X chromosome inactivation occurs randomly in each cell during early female embryonic development to achieve dosage compensation.","The X inactivation centre contains the XIST gene which produces non-coding RNA that coats and silences one X chromosome.","Once established, X inactivation is maintained through subsequent cell divisions via DNA methylation."],"references":["Ahn J, Lee J. X chromosome: X inactivation. Nature Education. 2008;1(1):24. Available at: https://www.nature.com/scitable/topicpage/x-chromosome-x-inactivation-323/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92506"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16071"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92506"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-29T10:55:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-29T10:55:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8762"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110235"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4935"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd5a","name":"Reprod